          <td valign="top" width="1" ><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="18" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td  valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <BR><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="cafda011f10985dc5cf765c436281bbe" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr height="10"><td width="98%" bgcolor="#333333" height="10"><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="6" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td><td valign="bottom" align="right"><img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/tk.gif" width="103" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td valign="top" align="right">
<img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/bk.gif" width="92" height="24" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The 5 Colors Of Magic<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.75)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=12451'>Jonathan "Morphling71" Newell</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=12451&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Ok, so as we all know there are 5 colors to Magic.  I am going to look at them as I would when Magic first came out, in order to gain a better understanding of them.  I am also going to provide a sample deck for each mono color as it would have been when Beta was first released. (please keep in mind that i am doing these decklists as they may have been before a banned/restricted list was ever instated).<br />
<br />
WHITE<br />
<br />
What is the firs thing that comes to mind when you think about white?  Good. Light. Justice. Order.  White features plenty of artifact and enchamtment removal.  It is know for having weenies, and the occational big creature.  IT has life gain, which can either be essential or irritating.  It has many sneaky tricks that can annoy an opponent.  It can be at the edge of defeat and gain 15 life like it&#39;s white&#39;s job (well, it is).  White is all about protecting itself too.  It has a circle of protection for each color and maby ways to prevent damage to creatures. It had Crusade, which was very solid, considering the power and toughness of its creatures.  Weenies could become huge and beat your head in before you knew what happened.  And then, Its huge creatures would drop to finish you off. Here is what a typical deck of the old days may look like...<br />
<br />
Plains x 20<br />
<br />
Mox Pearl x 2<br />
<br />
Serra Angel x 3<br />
Savannah Lions x 4<br />
Personal Incarnation x 3<br />
White Knight x 4<br />
<br />
Blessing x 4<br />
Disenchant x 4<br />
Crusade x 4<br />
Swords to Plowshares x 4<br />
Wrath of God x 4<br />
Healing Salve x 4<br />
<br />
BLUE<br />
<br />
Ah, good old blue.  You either love it or you hate it.  You love to be the one in control of the game with your counters, or you are the one who has nothing because it was all countered.  Blue is also about stealing.  It can steal half your board if you aren&#39;t careful.  It has enormously powerful draw spells, so it can usually keep a full hand.  It has a few big creatures.  Blue players are very Machivellian (which means they are sneaky).  They can also copy your creatures and artifacts if you are not careful.  What blue doesnt counter, it bounces, and what it doesnt bounce, it steals... Here is a typical Beta blue deck.<br />
<br />
Island x 20<br />
<br />
Mox Sapphire x 2<br />
<br />
Mahamotti Djinn x 4<br />
Clone x 4<br />
Vesuvian Doppelganger x 4<br />
<br />
Unsummon x 4<br />
Counterspell x 4<br />
Spell Blast x 4<br />
Ancestral Recall x 4<br />
Braingeyser x 2<br />
Time Walk x 4<br />
Control Magic x 4<br />
<br />
RED<br />
<br />
Yes, it&#39;s you buddy, Red.  Red has always been the color of burn and power.  It has dozens of removal spells and huge pumpable creatures.  I mean, come on... SHIVAN DRAGON!  Red wins by either clearing the board for its own creatures to beat your head in or it would simply burn you to death.  It usually combined the two, and if you werent careful, you were dead.  The one thing red hated was CoP red.  It could create MAJOR problems, but if you could get around that, you were usually OK.  Here is how you might have burned your opponent in the old days before Urza&#39;s Rage....<br />
<br />
Mountain x 20<br />
<br />
Mox Ruby x 2<br />
<br />
Shivan Dragon x 4<br />
Fire Elemental x 4<br />
Roc of Kher Ridges x 4<br />
Wall of Fire x 4<br />
<br />
Lightning Bolt x 4<br />
Fireball x 4<br />
Mana Flare x 4<br />
Disentigrate x 4<br />
Fork x 4<br />
Stone Rain x 2<br />
<br />
<br />
BLACK<br />
<br />
Ahhhh! It&#39;s Black!  NO!  Well, you are usually OK if this is the color you are playing.  Black really has no counterspells or drawing (except for a few noticeable cards such as Necro.)  Black was the color of evil.  It would destroy your lands, you creatures, your hand, artifacts... and well, everything.  Black is the color of discard.  Evil is lurking in the swamp, so watch out.  Black has plenty of creature destruction, land destruction, and its own creatures that can become huge if you are not careful.  It will more than likely destroy anything you put on the board.  It has fast mana acceleration and deadly spells to put the mana to use.  It can manipulate its graveyard and bring back creatures you thought were long gone.  It has plenty of creatures that regenerate, so they are hard to kill, even for red.  It can kill you quickly or slowly, but in general, it will just kill you... Here is a typical old school black deck...<br />
<br />
Swamp x 20<br />
<br />
Mox Jet x 2<br />
<br />
Hypnotic Specter x 4<br />
Sengir Vampire x 2<br />
Lord of the Pit x 2<br />
Black Knight x 4<br />
Royal Assassin x 4<br />
<br />
Drain Life x 2<br />
Dark Ritual x 4<br />
Unholy Strength x 2<br />
Terror x 4<br />
Mind Twist x 2<br />
Raise Dead x 2<br />
Demonit Tutor x 4<br />
Howl From Beyond x 2<br />
<br />
GREEN<br />
<br />
And, last but not least, we have green.  The old school power.  Nothing flashy or fancy, just pure old POWER.  Green has always had powerful creatures.  It can destroy lands and artifacts, as well as enchantments.  It can generate mana very quickly which can be devastaging to a slow deck.  It has some life gain, but it really doesn&#39;t need it.  It can take on flying creatures or just take them out.  Not too much more needs to be said, its just power....  here is your typical power green.<br />
<br />
Forest x 20<br />
<br />
Mox Emerald x 2<br />
<br />
Llanowar Elves x 4<br />
Birds of Paradise x 4<br />
Force of Nature x 4<br />
Craw Wurm x 4<br />
<br />
Regeneration x 4<br />
Stream of Life x 4<br />
Gian Growth x 4<br />
Fog x 4<br />
Hurricane x 2<br />
Instill Energy x 4<br />
<br />
Well, there you have it.  The 5 colors as they were in the days of BETA.  The original.  I hope this helps some of you beginners out.  This is the first part of a series, so that everyone can get a feel for how the colors form from their basics to the complex mix they are in today...  Next week I will attempt to analyse all the color combos:<br />
<br />
White-Blue<br />
White-Black<br />
WHite-Green<br />
White-Red<br />
Blue-Black<br />
Blue-Green<br />
Blue-Red<br />
Green-Red<br />
Green-Black<br />
Black-Red<br />
<br />
I will attempt to explain how they interact, and how to do an accurate mana curve, so you will never need to worry about not finding the right color... Well, Im off to Class, Ta Ta For Now....<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
